Here's how to implement all three requirements:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button (in `EditProductPage.xaml`)

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                            Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. Navigation Guard (in `AppShell.xaml.cs`)

Use `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` so you can `await` the dialog:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" â€” cancel navigation

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

### 3. ViewModel (`EditProductViewModel.cs`)

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        // This triggers OnNavigating above, which shows the guard
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }

    // Set HasUnsavedChanges = true whenever a form field changes
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`GetDeferral()`** is required because `DisplayAlert` is async â€” without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- **`args.Cancel()`** stops the navigation when the user picks "Stay".
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** replaces the default back-arrow tap, letting you route through `GoToAsync("..")` which still triggers the `OnNavigating` guard.
- The guard checks `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` so it only fires on back-navigation, not forward pushes.
